div.div:
Horizontal dotted lines represent version boundaries that temporarily must not be merged.
Reason: Each
transaction
must check for conflicts in commit versions newer than its snapshot. This check should not read into the original snapshot; or else false conflicts can be detected.
1. When a transaction establishes its initial snapshot, it holds the snapshot's upper boundary.
1. When a transaction checks for conflicts, it redefines its snapshot, holds the new snapshot's both upper and lower boundaries, and unholds any prior (further lower) boundary.
1. When a transaction finishes (whether it commits or not), it unholds its held boundaries (one or two of them).

ol.li:
Whenever the
F+C
worker replaces some existing nodes with a new node,

The replaced, now-dangling nodes are saved to be GC'd later. These nodes remain traversable, by
txns
that hold some list version within the range
(-inf ~ curr_list_ver].

The new node is traversable by
txns
that hold some list version within the range (-inf ~ +inf).
(Note, neither pushing nor inserting increments the current list version; only replacing does.)

Whenever each
txn
traverses the linked list,

It might traverse over any node whose upper-bound traversable list version is >= the txn's held list version. Each txn is agnostic about accessing any of the equivalent paths: pre- or post-replacement.
It unholds its held list version.

div.div:
Linked list design params
Linked list <-> Indexes:
Option A: The PI and the SIs each has its own linked list.
Option B: There is one global linked list, where each node contains the PI and all SIs.
Operations on the linked list:
By many
txns
:
Get one key-value entry => Read newest-to-older.
Get range of key-value entries => Read in either direction.
Check conflicts => Read the slice between the previously held snapshot and the newest end of the LL, in either direction.
Commit => Push a node at the newest end.
By one
F+C
job:
Read a snapshot, in either direction.
Replace a slice with a node.
By one
SICr
job:
Read a snapshot, in either direction.
Insert a node within the snapshot.
Singly-linked vs doubly-linked:
Newer-to-older traversal is needed.
Older-to-newer traversal is optional.
Advantage: It allows us to flexibly design how F+C prioritizes which slice of LL to work on.
Advantage: It is possible to maintain a boundary across which all older nodes are SSTables and all newer nodes are MemLogs. This, in turn, allows us to simplify the types.
MemLog --> Iterator< Item = (&K, &OptDatum<V>) >
SSTable --> Iterator< Item = Result<(K, OptDatum<V>)> >
